<Layout title="PM2: The Powerful Process Manager for Node.js and Python — Rupadana">
  <article class="reveal">
    <span class="tag">Process Management</span>
    <h1>PM2: The Powerful Process Manager for Node.js and Python</h1>
    <div class="meta">How to keep your web applications alive and performant in a production environment.</div>

    <div class="card article-content">
      <p>
        In a production environment, simply running a script in the background is not enough. You need 
        assurance that your application will automatically restart if it crashes, stay alive after 
        a server reboot, and allow for easy monitoring of logs and resource usage. This is where 
        <strong>PM2</strong> comes in.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        PM2 is a production process manager for Node.js applications with a built-in load balancer. 
        It allows you to keep applications alive forever, reload them without downtime, and facilitate 
        common system admin tasks.
      </div>

      <h2>Why Use a Process Manager?</h2>
      <p>
        When you run a command like <code>node app.js</code> or <code>python3 -m http.server</code>, the process 
        is tied to your current terminal session. If you close the terminal or if the process hits an 
        error and crashes, your website goes down. 
      </p>

      <p>
        PM2 solves this by daemonizing the application. It runs it in the background as a system service. 
        If the app crashes, PM2 immediately restarts it. If the server reboots, PM2 can automatically 
        resurrect all your saved processes.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Features of PM2</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Automatic Restart:</strong> If your app crashes or the VPS runs out of memory, PM2 will try to bring it back online.</li>
        <li><strong>Cluster Mode:</strong> Node.js is single-threaded. PM2's cluster mode allows you to spawn multiple instances of your app across all CPU cores, acting as a built-in load balancer.</li>
        <li><strong>Log Management:</strong> Easily view, flush, and manage logs for all your different services from a single interface.</li>
        <li><strong>Process Monitoring:</strong> Real-time monitoring of CPU and RAM usage for each individual process.</li>
        <li><strong>Startup Scripts:</strong> Generate and configure startup scripts to keep your apps running after a VPS restart.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Beyond Node.js: Managing Python and More</h2>
      <p>
        While built with Node.js in mind, PM2 is surprisingly versatile. It can manage any executable. 
        For example, if you are serving a static site using Python's built-in server, you can manage it 
        with PM2:
      </p>

      <pre><code>pm2 start "python3 -m http.server 3000" --name "my-blog"</code></pre>

      <p>
        This is exactly how I manage the portfolio site you are reading right now. It ensures that 
        even if the server experiences high load or a temporary crash, the blog remains accessible.
      </p>

      <h2>Managing Resource-Constrained Environments</h2>
      <p>
        On a VPS with limited RAM (like 2GB), PM2 is essential. It helps you identify which processes 
        are consuming too much memory and allows you to "save" a stable process list that can be 
        recovered if the OOM (Out of Memory) killer starts terminating processes.
      </p>

      <p>
        Commands like <code>pm2 status</code> and <code>pm2 monit</code> give you a clear dashboard 
        of your server's health at a glance.
      </p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>
        If you are moving from local development to a live VPS, PM2 should be one of the first 
        tools you install. It provides the stability and observability needed to run professional 
        web services without constant manual intervention.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

